50|$|At the {{beginning}} of the Third Reich, Cologne was considered difficult by <b>the</b> <b>Nazis</b> because of deep-rooted communist and Catholic influences in <b>the</b> city. <b>The</b> <b>Nazis</b> were always struggling for control of the city.|$|R
50|$|Marty's treason allowed <b>the</b> <b>Nazis</b> to also arrest Barlier, Doornik {{and most}} of the network, totaling 26 persons. The small {{intelligence}} network created by Max André, however, was untouched, and continued its operations until the Liberation of Paris in August 1944. For several weeks, Gaessler sent false information to London and allowed <b>the</b> <b>Nazis</b> to arrest several other agents. He was evacuated by <b>the</b> <b>Nazis</b> to Austria, and disappeared in 1945.|$|R
